doc/source/specs/bank-indexing.rst.message:
does this mean:
1. among multi sites, we only support eventual consistency in indices. This is reasonable since the bank itself(and most storage products do so) only provides eventual consistency cross sites;
2. in the local site, we only index in background and only provide eventual consistency between checkpoints and their indices. I'm not sure whether this is acceptable in a local environment for all cases. eg. For local backup case, user may want to list all available checkpoints at once instead of waiting without timing guarantee.

How about divide local indexing into two cases: 
1. system index: where we define several limited indices which are critical, like date, status, provider; Those indices will be built synchronously once checkpoints are CUD;
2. user defined index: like user defined tag, those indices will be built with eventual consistency;

doc/source/specs/proactive-bank-indexing.message:
We need identify the case:
1. the bank bankend supports replication with strong consistency;
2. the bank bankend supports replication with eventual consistency;
3. the bank bankend doesn't replicate but backup the bank somewhere else and we need import the backup on restore;

No matter for which case, the replication/backup will stop when DR happens.
I'm not sure why there's 'version' to identify indices.
IMHO, to read bank once after DR detected (bank replication/backup stops) and build indices during restoration will be enough?

